\begin{abstract}
The lack of determinism restricts the integration of safety-critical applications into edge–fog–cloud (EFC) architectures. Existing EFC schedulers are designed for dynamic, best-effort operation and focus primarily on computational placement, while communication is either abstracted or treated as a secondary cost term. Bounded-latency routing and deterministic task execution are seldom co-optimized under a unified timing model, limiting the provision of end-to-end timing guarantees.

This paper addresses these gaps by introducing a three-tier Time-Triggered Edge–Fog–Cloud (TTEFC) architecture that supports safety-critical workloads on a managed, deterministic substrate, using IEEE Time-Sensitive Networking (TSN) for intra-domain communication and IETF Deterministic Networking (DetNet) for routed inter-domain paths. Second, a hierarchical genetic algorithm (HGA) is presented to co-schedule (i) partition-to-cluster mapping, (ii) partition execution order, (iii) deterministic route selection for inter-partition flows, and (iv) per-partition time budgets that act as scheduling contracts for parallel partition-level optimizers. Third, an adaptive slack reallocation operator is proposed to redistribute temporal slack from over-satisfied partitions to budget violators, improving feasibility convergence without increasing the end-to-end deadline.

Experiments on synthetic DAG workloads (100–500 tasks) evaluate the proposed hierarchical genetic algorithm (HGA) against HEFT and round-robin. Under the evaluated platform and deterministic-network assumptions, the proposed HGA achieves lower global makespans, with up to 46.5\% and 18.9\% reduction relative to HEFT and round-robin, respectively. In addition, the specified application deadlines (2600/2700/4300 Time units (TU)) are met in all evaluated cases. In contrast, HEFT exceeds the deadline in all cases, and round-robin exceeds it in two of the three workload sizes.
\end{abstract}

