\section{Introduction}
\IEEEPARstart{T}{he} Edge–Fog–Cloud (EFC) continuum is increasingly adopted as an architectural model for distributed, data-intensive applications \cite{in2}. By distributing computation, storage, and networking capabilities from centralized cloud resources toward the network edge, EFC enables scalable processing of the massive data streams generated by the Internet of Things (IoT). In parallel, safety-critical domains such as industrial automation, automotive systems, and avionics, which are characterized by stringent timing constraints, are also undergoing data-centric transformations \cite{scs1}. Traditionally deployed on specialized platforms, these systems are facing new demands for scalability and connectivity, as well as lifecycle challenges associated with rapid hardware obsolescence.
Migrating safety-critical logic onto distributed EFC infrastructures promises substantial benefits. However, it exposes a fundamental conflict between best-effort EFC design principles and the determinism required by safety-critical systems. This conflict is referred to as the determinism gap: safety-critical workloads require strict end-to-end timing guarantees that state-of-the-art EFC architectures were not originally designed to provide \cite{in1}.

The primary value proposition of state-of-the-art EFC architectures is their dynamism, including elastic resource allocation \cite{in3,in4} and adaptation to fluctuating workloads \cite{in5}. Such dynamism is well suited to best-effort applications, such as streaming analytics or mobile computing, where average-case performance, cost, or energy consumption are the dominant objectives \cite{in6}. However, for safety-critical workloads, the heterogeneous and time-varying nature of EFC environments \cite{in7}, together with resource contention \cite{in8} and on-demand resource sharing, makes it difficult to establish end-to-end timing guarantees. While existing heuristic approaches \cite{in7} and AI-based schedulers \cite{AI1} can perform well under volatility, they typically optimize expected performance metrics and do not provide formally validated worst-case timing bounds; moreover, some approaches incur computational overhead that is incompatible with time-sensitive decision making.

This determinism gap is not limited to computation; it also arises in the network fabric, where latency and jitter must be bounded to achieve end-to-end guarantees. End-to-end timing guarantees cannot be established if communication delays remain uncontrolled. Standard EFC deployments typically rely on best-effort communication mechanisms and application-layer messaging, which provide no strict bounds on message latency or jitter \cite{cc2}. In safety-critical settings, such uncertainty complicates validation because late or missing messages can violate timing assumptions.

Determinism can be ensured by a time-triggered (TT) approach, which assumes a communication substrate with bounded latency and jitter. In this work, this substrate is realized by combining two established standards. Time-Sensitive Networking (TSN), specified in IEEE 802.1, provides deterministic, time-critical delivery over standard Ethernet at Layer 2 by enabling precise time synchronization, traffic scheduling, and resource reservation \cite{tsn1,tsn2}. TSN has become a widely adopted, interoperable basis for industrial automation, intended to replace proprietary fieldbuses \cite{tsn3}. However, EFC communication paths are typically multi-hop and routed, such that Layer 2 guarantees alone do not cover the full end-to-end path. This limitation is addressed by Deterministic Networking (DetNet), standardized by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF), which extends TSN-like properties to Layer 3 by providing bounded latency, bounded jitter, and controlled loss over routed segments \cite{det1,det2}. Together, TSN and DetNet provide the bounded-latency communication substrate on which the proposed TTEFC architecture relies. With communication latency and jitter bounded, end-to-end timing guarantees depend primarily on the scheduling algorithm.


