It is crucial to distinguish the scope of this work from general-purpose, best-effort cloud computing. Safety-critical workloads require determinism that cannot be guaranteed on shared public infrastructure, where contention and jitter are unbounded. The proposed TTEFC architecture targets managed, deterministic EFC deployments, in which determinism is provided through operator-controlled provisioning rather than assumed to be an inherent cloud property \cite{det1,sys1}. In this model, the underlying infrastructure must expose a Deterministic Communication Interface (DCI) through which bounded-latency communication and time synchronization can be requested and enforced. Such capabilities are increasingly supported by standards and ongoing network evolution, including IETF Deterministic Networking (DetNet) for bounded-latency forwarding over Layer 3 and emerging 3GPP mechanisms for time synchronization services (e.g., Release 18 Time Synchronization as a Service, TSaaS) \cite{sys1}. Consequently, DCI compliance is treated as an infrastructure responsibility of the provider/operator. Given a DCI-compliant substrate, the proposed HGA translates application DAGs into resource allocations and path selections that can be enforced by the underlying TSN/DetNet communication fabric.

Assuming a deterministic TSN/DetNet substrate, the remaining problem is to synthesize an end-to-end schedule that jointly accounts for task execution and communication. This problem is NP-hard \cite{sch1}. Common baselines such as HEFT \cite{sch2} and the GA formulations used as EFC baselines \cite{in1} do not explicitly model deterministic route selection or adaptive cross-partition time-budget negotiation. Accordingly, two gaps are identified in the state of the art.

First, a decoupled design is commonly employed. As noted in existing surveys, many scheduling techniques treat task allocation and communication routing as separate—often sequential—optimization problems \cite{in7}. In typical EFC baselines, including standard GA formulations, optimization is primarily driven by a compute-centric objective such as makespan \cite{sch2}, while communication is represented by simplified delay terms rather than explicit deterministic route selection. This separation can produce schedules that appear locally optimal at the compute level yet induce communication patterns that exceed end-to-end deadlines or create contention along shared links, which is not captured by a decoupled model.

Second, adaptive time-budget negotiation across partitions is not explicitly modeled. State-of-the-art schedulers generally do not provide a formal mechanism for cross-partition temporal feedback and adjustment. When one partition is over-satisfied and another violates its budget, temporal slack is not systematically redistributed, and feasibility recovery is left to unguided perturbations. The absence of an explicit slack reallocation mechanism, as discussed in \cite{sch5}, reduces the ability to steer the search toward feasible end-to-end schedules in hierarchical settings.

