This subsection describes the reconstruction step that integrates partition schedules and inserts inter-partition transmissions under deterministic routing. Algorithm~\ref{alg:SystemReconstruct} summarizes this procedure.

For each inter-partition message $m_{u,v}\in\mathcal{M}_{inter}$, the sender and receiver End Systems are identified from the task mappings, and a feasible candidate path is selected using the route-index hint $\rho[m_{u,v}]$. If the hinted index is invalid, the path with minimum latency is selected. The message arrival time is computed as $end(u)$ plus the bounded latency of the selected path, and the consumer task is constrained to start no earlier than this arrival time. Messages for which no feasible deterministic path exists are recorded as inter-partition communication violations. The global makespan $MS_{global}$ is computed as the latest completion time over all tasks after enforcing these arrival constraints.

Here, $IPCviol$ denotes the set of inter-partition communication violations, i.e., messages in $\mathcal{M}_{inter}$ for which no feasible deterministic path exists.

\subsection{Partition-Level Scheduler}
\label{sec:method_partition}

Once the system-level scheduler fixes the allocation $\Phi(p)$ and time budget $TB(p)$ for a partition $p$, a local optimization is performed to construct a feasible schedule within the assigned execution domain. Each partition-level scheduler operates independently and can be executed in parallel for different partitions. Its role is to determine a precedence-feasible task order, a task-to-End-System mapping within the allocated domain, and the corresponding intra-partition communication decisions while respecting the local time budget.

For each partition $p$, the local optimization problem is to minimize the partition makespan subject to the assigned scheduling contract:
\begin{equation}
\min \; (ms^p)
\qquad \text{s.t.} \qquad ms^p \le TB(p).
\label{eq:local_obj}
\end{equation}
$ms^p$ denotes the completion time of the last task in partition $p$, whereas $TB(p)$ is the time budget assigned by the system-level scheduler. Schedules that exceed the assigned budget are treated as locally infeasible and contribute a violation term during the system-level evaluation.

To solve this problem, a genetic search is applied at the partition level. Each local individual is encoded as
\begin{equation}
g^p = [\,\sigma^p \mid \phi_p \mid \eta^p \mid \xi^p\,],
\end{equation}
where $\sigma^p$ is a precedence-feasible task order, $\phi_p$ is the mapping of tasks to End Systems within the allocated domain $\Phi(p)$, $\eta^p$ defines local message priorities, and $\xi^p$ stores the candidate-path indices used for intra-partition communications. The fitness of a local individual is defined as
\begin{equation}
fit(g^p)=\left(ms^p,\; \max(0,ms^p-TB(p))\right),
\label{eq:local_fitness}
\end{equation}
which simultaneously favors short makespans and penalizes budget overruns.

Algorithm~\ref{alg:PartitionLevelGA} summarizes the partition-level scheduler.
The partition-level search begins by generating an initial population of valid local individuals. The task-order component $\sigma^p$ is initialized using random topological orders derived from the precedence relations in $JD^p$, thereby ensuring that all local individuals satisfy intra-partition dependencies from the outset. The mapping component $\phi_p$ assigns tasks only to End Systems belonging to the execution domain selected by $\Phi(p)$, while $\eta^p$ and $\xi^p$ initialize message priorities and local path selections for intra-partition communications.

\begin{algorithm}[H]
\caption{\textproc{PartitionLevelScheduler}}
\label{alg:PartitionLevelGA}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Require partition $p$; $(PT^p,\mathcal{M}_{intra}^p,JD^p)$; $(alloc{=}\Phi(p),tb{=}TB(p))$;
\Statex \hspace{\algorithmicindent} path catalogs $\{\mathcal{P}_{s,r}\}$; inner GA params $(N_{pop}^{(p)},N_{gen}^{(p)},p_{cx}^{(p)},p_{mut}^{(p)})$
\Ensure Local schedule $sched^p$, local makespan $ms^p$, and task mapping $\phi_p$
\State \textbf{Genome:} $g^p=[\,\sigma^p \mid \phi_p \mid \eta^p \mid \xi^p\,]$
\State $Pop^p \gets \textproc{InitLocalPopulation}(p,\Phi(p))$
\State $best^p \gets \varnothing$;\quad $bestMS^p \gets +\infty$
\For{$gen=1$ to $N_{gen}^{(p)}$}
  \ForAll{$g^p \in Pop^p$}
    \State $(sched^p_g, ms^p_g, \phi^g_p) \gets \textproc{ReconstructPartition}$
    \Statex \hspace{\algorithmicindent} $(JD^p,g^p,PT^p,\mathcal{M}_{intra}^p,\{\mathcal{P}_{s,r}\})$ \Comment{Alg.~\ref{alg:PartitionReconstruct}}
    \State $fit(g^p) \gets \big(ms^p_g,\max(0,ms^p_g-TB(p))\big)$
    \If{$ms^p_g < bestMS^p$}
      \State $best^p \gets g^p$;\quad $bestMS^p \gets ms^p_g$
    \EndIf
  \EndFor
  \State $Parents^p \gets \textproc{TournamentSelect}(Pop^p, fit)$
  \State $Offspring^p \gets \textproc{CrossoverLocal}(Parents^p)$
  \State $Offspring^p \gets \textproc{MutateLocal}(Offspring^p)$
  \State $Pop^p \gets \textproc{SelectNextLocal}(Parents^p \cup Offspring^p, N_{pop}^{(p)})$
\EndFor
\State $(sched^p, ms^p, \phi_p) \gets \textproc{ReconstructPartition}$
\Statex \hspace{\algorithmicindent} $(JD^p,best^p,PT^p,\mathcal{M}_{intra}^p,\{\mathcal{P}_{s,r}\})$
\State \Return $(sched^p, ms^p, \phi_p)$
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}


At each generation, every local individual is evaluated through a deterministic reconstruction step that converts the encoded order, mapping, and communication choices into a concrete schedule. The resulting local makespan $ms^p$ is then combined with the budget-overrun term $\max(0,ms^p-TB(p))$ to compute the local fitness according to (\ref{eq:local_fitness}). The evolutionary process then applies selection, crossover, and mutation operators that preserve precedence feasibility and allocation validity. Once the local search terminates, the best reconstructed schedule is returned to the system-level scheduler, together with its realized task mapping and makespan.




For a fixed genome, the reconstruction procedure deterministically produces a unique local schedule. The start time of each task is
computed solely from predecessor completion times, communication latencies along the selected paths, and the availability of the
assigned End System. Consequently, the resulting makespan and any budget violation depend only on the decisions encoded in the genome. This determinism ensures consistent evaluation of individuals at the system level and allows scheduling decisions to be compared reliably during the evolutionary search.

{\footnotesize
\begin{algorithm}[H]
\caption{\textproc{ReconstructPartition (Local Reconstruction)}}
\label{alg:PartitionReconstruct}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Require $JD^p$; genome $g^p=\langle \sigma^p,\phi_p,\eta^p,\xi^p\rangle$; $PT^p$; $\mathcal{M}_{intra}^p$; path catalogs $\{\mathcal{P}_{s,r}\}$
\Ensure $sched^p$ (task and intra-partition message times), $ms^p$
\State \textbf{Init} $next\_free[q]\gets 0$ for every End System $q$ used in $\phi_p$
\ForAll{task $t$ in $\sigma^p$}
  \State $q \gets \phi_p[t]$
    \State $\text{predReady} \gets\quad \max\limits_{u \in Pred(t)} \Big(\qquad \underbrace{end(u)}_{\text{finish of }u}$
    \Statex $\qquad +\;
    \underbrace{\text{latency}\!\left(
    \textproc{SelectPath}(\xi^p[m_{u,t}],\mathcal{P}_{\phi_p(u),q}),\, m_{u,t}
    \right)}_{\text{path latency for }m_{u,t}}$
    \Statex $\quad \Big)$ \Comment{$0$ if $Pred(t)=\varnothing$}
  \State $\text{procReady} \gets next\_free[q]$
  \State $start(t)\gets \max(\text{predReady}, \text{procReady})$
  \State $end(t)\gets start(t) + PT^p(t,q)$
  \State $next\_free[q] \gets end(t)$
  \ForAll{intra-partition msgs $m: t\!\to\! v$ in $\mathcal{M}_{intra}^p$ (ordered by $\eta^p[m]$)}
     \State $q_v \gets \phi_p[v]$
     \State $path \gets \textproc{SelectPath}(\xi^p[m], \mathcal{P}_{q,q_v})$ \Comment{Alg.~\ref{alg:SelectPath}}
     \State $tx\_s(m)\gets end(t)$
     \State $tx\_e(m)\gets tx\_s(m) + \text{latency}(path,m)$
     \State enforce $start(v)\gets \max(start(v), tx\_e(m))$ \Comment{propagate to successors if needed}
  \EndFor
\EndFor
\State $ms^p \gets \max\limits_{t} \, end(t)$
\State \Return $sched^p, ms^p$
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}
}

\subsection{Local Schedule Reconstruction}
\label{sec:method_partition_reconstruct}

Given a local genome $g^p=[\,\sigma^p \mid \phi_p \mid \eta^p \mid \xi^p\,]$, the reconstruction procedure deterministically constructs the
schedule of partition $p$ by assigning start and completion times to all tasks and by inserting the corresponding intra-partition transmissions.

The reconstruction must satisfy three conditions:(i) precedence feasibility between tasks, (ii) exclusive use of each End System, and (iii) causal consistency of intra-partition communications.



Tasks are processed according to the precedence-feasible order encoded in $\sigma^p$. For each task $t$, the earliest feasible
start time is computed as the maximum between processor availability and the arrival time of all incoming messages. The assigned End System is determined by $\phi_p(t)$, while the communication latency of each incoming message is derived from the candidate path selected through the path-index vector $\xi^p$.

Once a task is scheduled, all outgoing intra-partition messages are inserted according to the message-priority vector $\eta^p$. The resulting message transmission times are then propagated to successor tasks to ensure that no task starts before all required data has arrived.

The partition makespan $ms^p$ is finally obtained as the maximum completion time among all tasks in the reconstructed schedule. Algorithm~\ref{alg:PartitionReconstruct} summarizes this procedure.



\subsection{Time-Budget Mutation and Slack Distribution}
\label{sec:method_tb}

A key innovation in the system-level GA is the time-budget mutation operator described in Algorithm~\ref{alg:MutateTB}, which dynamically
adjusts the partition time budgets to improve convergence. Instead of applying blind mutation to the time-budget vector, the
operator redistributes slack among partitions based on the feedback obtained from the previous evaluation.

\begin{algorithm}[H]
\caption{\textproc{MutateTimeBudget}}
\label{alg:MutateTB}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Require individual $ind=[\,\pi \mid \Phi \mid \rho \mid TB\,]$ with stored
         partition makespans $makespans[p]$ and violations $viol[p]$
\Ensure Updated $TB$ aligned with permutation $\pi$

\State \textbf{Parameters:} margin ratios, stability-band limits,
step gains, and bounded perturbation factor

\For{$i=0$ to $|\pi|-1$}
  \State $p \gets \pi[i]$
  \State $tb \gets TB[i]$
  \State $ms \gets makespans[p]$
  \State $v \gets viol[p]$

  \State $target \gets ms(1+\delta)$ \Comment{safety margin}
  \State define stability band $(band_{lo}, band_{hi})$ around $target$

  \If{$v>0$ \textbf{or} $tb < ms$} \Comment{deficit}
      \State increase $TB[i]$ proportionally toward $target$
  \ElsIf{$tb \ge band_{hi}$} \Comment{surplus}
      \State decrease $TB[i]$ proportionally toward $band_{lo}$
  \ElsIf{$tb < target$}
      \State slightly increase $TB[i]$ toward $band_{lo}$
  \Else
      \State keep $TB[i]$ unchanged
  \EndIf

  \State optionally apply a small bounded perturbation
\EndFor

\State \Return $TB$
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

During mutation, partitions that finish significantly earlier than their assigned budget act as \emph{donors}, whereas partitions whose
execution time approaches or exceeds their allocated budget act as \emph{receivers}. A portion of the slack from donor partitions is
transferred to receiver partitions by tightening the donor budgets and relaxing the receiver budgets accordingly. This redistribution preserves
the overall temporal structure of the schedule while shifting idle time toward partitions that require additional execution margin.

By continuously balancing slack among partitions, the system-level search can escape stagnation caused by poor initial budget assignments.
Over successive generations, the mutation operator progressively stabilizes the budget distribution so that partitions neither suffer
from excessive deadline pressure nor accumulate unnecessary slack. Empirically, this results in faster convergence toward feasible
end-to-end schedules because the evolutionary search avoids exploring obviously infeasible budget allocations.


\section{Performance Evaluation}
\label{sec:results}
This section evaluates the proposed hierarchical genetic algorithm (HGA) with respect to end-to-end schedulability, global makespan, and convergence behavior. The evaluation is organized into two parts. First, the proposed method is benchmarked against established scheduling baselines under the baseline deadlines of the considered workloads. Second, a sensitivity analysis examines the behavior of the adaptive slack reallocation mechanism under progressively tightened deadlines.

\subsection{Evaluation Setup}

The proposed scheduler was implemented in Python 3.10 using the DEAP evolutionary computation framework \cite{r1}. The evaluation used synthetic directed acyclic graph (DAG) workloads with 100, 250, and 500 tasks. The use of synthetic DAGs is well established in scheduling research, where generators such as TGFF \cite{r4} and SDF3 \cite{r5} are widely used to enable controlled and repeatable benchmarking across diverse application structures. Following this methodology, the DAGs in this work were generated using the Stanford Network Analysis Platform (SNAP), which supports systematic variation in graph size and structural properties, including dependency density and in- and out-degree distributions. This enables reproducible evaluation across heterogeneous workload patterns while preserving comparability with prior DAG-based scheduling studies.

These workloads were evaluated on a fixed edge--fog--cloud platform model represented as a graph of compute and communication resources. The compute infrastructure comprises one edge--fog domain (FE) and three cloud clusters (C1, C2, and C3). For the communication infrastructure, a finite set of deterministic candidate routes was computed offline on the platform graph using a K-shortest-path method for each relevant source--destination pair. During scheduling, routing decisions were then made by selecting from this precomputed path catalog. The same platform model was used across all workload sizes and deadline settings, so the observed performance differences are attributable to scheduling decisions rather than changes in the underlying execution infrastructure.

Within this model, application DAG vertices represent tasks and DAG edges represent inter-task messages. Tasks are associated with execution-time parameters, such as worst-case execution times, while messages incur deterministic communication costs once routing paths are selected from the precomputed path catalog. This allows both computation placement and communication-path selection to be evaluated consistently within the same scheduling framework.

The baseline application deadlines were derived from the makespan of an initial list-scheduling heuristic applied to each workload and correspond to the 100\% deadline setting used in the main benchmark comparison. The baseline deadlines were set to 2600, 2700, and 4300 TU for the 100T, 250T, and 500T workloads, respectively. Additional experiments with tightened deadlines of 90\%, 80\%, and 70\% of these baseline values are presented later in the sensitivity analysis to evaluate the robustness of the proposed approach under reduced timing slack.

At the system level, the optimization jointly minimizes total partition budget violations and global lateness, where lateness is defined as the difference between the global makespan and the application deadline. At the partition level, the local scheduler minimizes partition makespan while penalizing partition budget overruns. This objective hierarchy aligns with the hierarchical feasibility model, in which partition-level schedules are treated as local temporal contracts within the end-to-end reconstruction process.

