\begin{IEEEbiography}[{\includegraphics[width=1in,height=1.25in,clip,keepaspectratio]{Daniel.jpeg}}]{Daniel Onwuchekwa}~received the Ph.D.\ degree in Electrical Engineering and Computer Science from the University of Siegen, Germany, in 2020. He is currently a Postdoctoral Researcher and Project Manager at the Division of Embedded Systems, University of Siegen, Germany. His doctoral research, supervised by Prof. Roman Obermaisser, focused on developing a fault injection framework for time-triggered systems. He has contributed to several European research projects, including SAFE4RAIL, Ecomobility, and FRACTAL where he served as a Work Package Leader. His current research interests encompass system architectures for distributed embedded real-time systems, fault-tolerant design, and embedded artificial intelligence (AI) in real-time embedded systems.
\end{IEEEbiography}
\vspace{-8pt}

\begin{IEEEbiography}[{\includegraphics[width=1in,height=1.25in,clip,keepaspectratio]{prof.png}}]{Roman Obermaisser}~is a Full Professor at the Division for Embedded Systems of the University of Siegen.
He studied Computer Science at the Vienna University of Technology, receiving the Master's degree in 2001 and the doctoral degree in 2004 under Prof.\ Hermann Kopetz. In 2009, he received the habilitation (``Venia docendi'') in Technical Computer Science. His research focuses on system architectures for distributed embedded real-time systems. He is the author of numerous journal and conference publications and a book on an integrated time-triggered architecture (Springer). He has participated in many EU projects (e.g., SAFEPOWER, universAAL, DECOS, NextTTA) and coordinated the projects DREAMS, GENESYS, and ACROSS.
